The '''Cotswolds''' are a range of [[hill]]s in west-central England, sometimes called the &quot;Heart of England&quot;, an area {{convert|25|mi|km|0}} across and {{convert|90|mi|km|0}} long. The area has been designated as the Cotswold [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]]. The highest point in the Cotswolds range is [[Cleeve Hill]] at {{convert|1083|ft|m|0|abbr=on}},&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cleevecommon.org.uk/200702/about-land.html|title=Landscape|publisher=Cleeve Common|accessdate=12 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; {{convert|2.5|mi|km|0}} to the north of [[Cheltenham]]. 

The Cotswolds lie mainly within the [[ceremonial counties of England|ceremonial counties]] of [[Gloucestershire]] and [[Oxfordshire]], but extend into parts of [[Wiltshire]], [[Somerset]], [[Worcestershire]] and [[Warwickshire]].

==Toponymy==
The name Cotswold is sometimes attributed the meaning &quot;sheep enclosure in rolling hillsides&quot;,&lt;ref&gt;[http://books.google.com/booksid=FnyMWqlgw8QC&amp;pg=PA286&amp;lpg=PA286&amp;dq=cotswolds+etymology&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=RM1QlZC8DH&amp;sig=7cQr_TwaOWC_YxJP78bLRDFwJuo Let's Go Britain]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | url= http://books.google.com/books?id=apcmAAAAMAAJ | title= ‪Local etymology: a derivative dictionary of geographical names‬ | first= Richard Stephen ‬ | last= Charnock | publisher= Houlston and Wright | year= 1859‬ | pages= 76}}&lt;/ref&gt; 
incorporating the term &quot;[[The Wolds|wold]]&quot; meaning hills. The [[English Place-Name Society]] has for many years accepted that the term Cotswold is derived from ''Codesuualt'' of the twelfth century or other variations on this form, the etymology of which was given 'Cod's-wold', which is 'Cod's high open land'.&lt;ref&gt;Smith, A. H. 1964 The Place-Names of Gloucestershire, part 1: The Rivers and Road-names, the East Cotswolds, Cambridge, p.2&lt;/ref&gt; Cod was interpreted as an Old English personal name, which can be recognised in further names: [[Cutsdean]], Codeswellan, and Codesbyrig, some of which date back to the eighth century AD.&lt;ref&gt;Smith A. H. 1964 The Place-Names of Gloucestershire part 2: The North and West Cotswolds, Cambridge pp.7-8&lt;/ref&gt; It has subsequently been noticed that &quot;Cod&quot; could philologically derive from a Brittonic female cogname &quot;Cuda&quot;, which is the name of a mother goddess recognised in the Cotswold region.&lt;ref&gt;Yeates, S. J. 2008 The Tribe of Witches: The Religion of the Dobunni and the Hwicce pp.11-18&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Yeates, S. J. 2006 River-Names, Celtic and Old English: their dual medieval and post-medieval personalities, Journal of the English Place-Name Society 38, pp.63-81&lt;/ref&gt;

==Description==
[[image:Bibury Cottages in the Cotswolds - June 2007.jpg|thumb|Bibury: a typical Cotswold Village]]
The spine of the Cotswolds runs south west to north east through six counties, particularly Gloucestershire, west Oxfordshire, and south western Warwickshire. The northern and western edges of the Cotswolds are marked by steep [[escarpment]]s down to the [[River Severn|Severn valley]] and the [[River Avon, Warwickshire|Warwickshire Avon]]. This escarpment or scarp feature, sometimes called the '''Cotswold Edge''', is a result of the uplifting (tilting) of the limestone layer, exposing its broken edge.&lt;ref name=&quot;cotsstone&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://thecotswoldgateway.co.uk/cotswoldstone.htm|title=Cotswold Stone|publisher=Cotswold Gateway|accessdate=12 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; This is a [[cuesta]], in [[geology|geological]] terms. The [[dip slope]] is to the south east. On the eastern boundary lies the city of [[Oxford]] and on the west is [[Stroud, England|Stroud]]. To the south-east the upper reaches of the [[Thames Valley]] and towns such as [[Lechlade]], [[Tetbury]] and [[Fairford]] are often considered to mark the limit of this region. To the south the Cotswolds, with the characteristic uplift of the Cotswold Edge, reach beyond [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], and towns such as [[Chipping Sodbury]] and [[Marshfield, South Gloucestershire|Marshfield]] share elements of Cotswold character.

The area is characterised by attractive small [[town]]s and [[village]]s built of the underlying ''[[Cotswold stone]]'' (a yellow [[oolite|oolitic]] [[limestone]]).&lt;ref name=&quot;cotsstone&quot;/&gt; This limestone is rich in [[fossils]], in particular fossilised [[sea urchins]]. In the [[Middle Ages]] the [[wool]] trade made the Cotswolds prosperous. Some of this money was put into the building of [[Church (building)|churches]] so the area has a number of large handsome Cotswold stone &quot;[[wool church]]es&quot;. The area remains affluent and has attracted wealthy people who own [[Vacation property|second homes]] in the area or have chosen to retire there.

Cotswold towns include [[Bourton-on-the-Water]], [[Broadway, Worcestershire|Broadway]], [[Burford]],  [[Chipping Norton, Oxfordshire|Chipping Norton]], [[Cirencester]], [[Moreton-in-Marsh]], [[Northleach]], [[Stow-on-the-Wold]], [[Stroud, Gloucestershire|Stroud]] and [[Winchcombe]]. The town of [[Chipping Campden]] is notable for being the home of the [[Arts and Crafts movement]], founded by [[William Morris]] at the end of the 19th and beginning of the 20th centuries.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.courtbarn.org.uk/history|title=History |publisher=Court Barn Museum|accessdate=6 April 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; William Morris lived occasionally in [[Broadway Tower]] a folly now part of a country park.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cotswoldswebsite.com/broadway-tower.htm|title=Broadway Tower|publisher=Cotswold website|accessdate=12 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt; Chipping Campden is also known for the annual [[Cotswold Olimpick Games]], a celebration of sports and games dating back to the early 17th century.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.olimpickgames.co.uk/contentok.php?id=862|title=Origins of Robert Dover's Games |publisher=Olympick Games|accessdate=12 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty==
[[Image:Cotswolds Cleeve Common.jpg|thumb|From Cleeve Common, near the highest point in the Cotswolds]]
The Cotswolds were designated an [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] (AONB) in 1966, with an expansion on 21 December 1990 to {{convert|1990|km2|sqmi|0}}. In 1991, all AONBs were measured again using modern methods. The official area of the Cotswolds AONB increased to {{convert|2038|km2|sqmi|0}}. In 2000, the government confirmed that AONBs had the same landscape quality and status as National Parks.&lt;ref name=&quot;aonb&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cotswoldsaonb.org.uk/?page=AONB|title=AONB|publisher=Cotswolds AONB|accessdate=12 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;
The Cotswolds AONB, which is the largest in England and Wales, stretches from the border regions of South Warwickshire and Worcestershire, through West Oxfordshire and Gloucestershire and takes in parts of Wiltshire, and [[Bath and North East Somerset]] in the South.
Gloucestershire County Council is responsible for 63 per cent of the AONB.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.naturalengland.org.uk/ourwork/conservation/designatedareas/aonb/cotswolds.aspx Cotswolds] ''[[Natural England]]''&lt;/ref&gt;

The Cotswolds Conservation Board is the organisation that exists to conserve and enhance the AONB. Established in 2004, the board carries out a range of work from securing funding for 'on the ground' conservation projects to providing a strategic overview of the area for key decision makers, such as planning officials. The board is an independent organisation funded by Natural England and the 17 local authorities that sit within the AONB.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.cotswoldsaonb.org.uk/?page=ccb|title=Cotswolds Conservation Board|publisher=Cotswolds AONB|accessdate=12 December 2009}}&lt;/ref&gt;

While the beauty of the Cotswold AONB is intertwined with the villages that seem to almost grow out of the landscape, the Cotswolds were primarily designated an [[Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]] for the rare limestone grassland habitats as well as the old growth beech woodlands that typify the area. These habitat areas are also the last refuge for many other flora and fauna with some so endangered they are protected under the [[Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981]]. [[Cleeve Hill]], and its associated commons, is a fine example of a limestone grassland and it is one of the few locations where the Duke of Burgundy butterfly can still be found in abundance.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Natural Areas - 55 Cotswolds|url=http://www.naturalareas.naturalengland.org.uk/science/natural/NA_Details.asp?NA_Id=55|publisher=Natural England|accessdate=6 May 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt;  The uniqueness and value of the Cotswolds is engendered in the fact that five European [[Special Areas of Conversation]], three [[National Nature Reserves]] and over 80 [[Sites of Specific Interest]] are contained within the Cotswold AONB.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Understanding the Cotswold AONB|url=http://www.cotswoldsaonb.org.uk/?page=aonb|publisher=Cotswolds Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty|accessdate=6 May 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; 

The [[Cotswold Voluntary Wardens]] Service, now part of the Cotswolds Conservation Board, was established in 1968 to help conserve and enhance the area and now has over 300 wardens.

The [[Cotswold Way]] is a long-distance footpath, approximately {{convert|103|mi|km|0}} long, running the length of the AONB mainly on the edge of the Cotswold escarpment with views over the [[Severn Valley (England)|Severn Valley]] and the [[Vale of Evesham]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url= http://www.nationaltrail.co.uk/Cotswold/text.asp?PageId=2 | title= Cotswold Way - About this trail | work= National Trail | accessdate= 2007-06-30 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

