==Transport==
[[Image:Cotswold roads 1933.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Map of Cotswolds roads from 1933]]
The Cotswolds lies between the [[M5 motorway|M5]], [[M40 motorway|M40]] and [[M4 motorway]]s. The main non-motorway roads through the area are the [[A46 road|A46]]: [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]] — [[Stroud, Gloucestershire|Stroud]] — [[Cheltenham]]; the [[A419 road|A419]]: [[Swindon]] — [[Cirencester]] — Stroud; the [[A429 road|A429]]: Cirencester — [[Stow-on-the-Wold]] — [[Moreton-in-Marsh]]; and the [[A40 road|A40]]: [[Oxford]] — [[Burford]] — Cheltenham. These all roughly follow the routes of ancient roads, some laid down by the [[Ancient Rome|Romans]], such as [[Ermin Street]] and the [[Fosse Way]].

The area is bounded by two major rail routes: in the south by the main [[Great Western Main Line|Bristol-Bath-London High Speed line]] and in the west by the [[Cross Country Route (MR)|Bristol-Birmingham main line]]. In addition, the [[Cotswold Line]] runs through the Cotswolds from Oxford to [[Worcester]], and the [[Golden Valley Line]] runs from Swindon to [[Gloucester]], carrying high speed and local services.

Main-line, high-speed rail services to the big cities run from stations such as [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], Swindon, Oxford, Cheltenham and Worcester. High-speed services to London are also available from [[Kemble railway station|Kemble station]] near Cirencester, [[Kingham railway station|Kingham station]] near Stow-on-the-Wold, [[Charlbury railway station|Charlbury station]] and [[Moreton-in-Marsh railway station|Moreton-in-Marsh station]].

Cheltenham, which is located just West of the Cotswolds, is a hub for [[National Express]] coach services. There are local bus services across the area, but some are infrequent. The best sources of information are the Gloucestershire County Council website,&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.gloucestershire.gov.uk/index.cfm?articleid=12503 Cotswold bus times]&lt;/ref&gt; or local [[Visitor center|tourist information centres]].

==The Cotswolds in cultural life and media==

The Cotswold region has inspired some of England's finest composers. In the early 1900s, [[Herbert Howells]] and [[Ivor Gurney]] used to go for long walks together over the hills and Gurney urged Howells to make the landscape, including the nearby [[Malvern Hills]], the inspiration for his future work. True to his word, in 1916, Howells wrote his first major piece, the Piano Quartet in A minor, inspired by the magnificent view of the [[Malvern Hills|Malverns]] - it was dedicated to &quot;the hill at Chosen ([[Churchdown]]) and Ivor Gurney who knows it&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http://uk.geocities.com/supernaturaltv/long_remembered_hills.htm&amp;date=2009-10-25+04:31:19  Long Remembered Hills] How the English composers Ivor Gurney and Herbert Howells were influenced by the Gloucestershire countryside.&lt;/ref&gt; Another contemporary of theirs, [[Gerald Finzi]], lived in nearby [[Painswick]]. The film ''[[Better Things (2008 film)|Better Things]]'', directed by Duane Hopkins, is set in a small Cotswold village. The fictional [[Agatha Raisin]] lives in the fictional village of Carsely in the Cotswolds.

