      <text xml:space="preserve">'''Clitoridectomy''' is the [[surgery|surgical]] removal of the [[clitoris]]. It is rarely needed as a therapeutic medical procedure, such as when [[cancer]] has developed in or spread to the clitoris. Most removals of the clitoris occur as [[female genital cutting]], defined by the [[World Health Organisation]] as ''&quot;all procedures involving partial or total removal of the external female genitalia or other injury to the female genital organs whether for cultural, religious or other non-therapeutic reasons.&quot;''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite press release 
  | title = New study shows female genital mutilation exposes women and babies to significant risk at childbirth
  | publisher = World Health Organization
  |date=2006-06-02
  | url = http://www.who.int/mediacentre/news/releases/2006/pr30/en/index.html
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

It was once used as a treatment for [[Masturbation#Female|female masturbation]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal|doi=10.1001/jama.1963.63710030028012|last=Duffy|first=John|date=October 19, 1963|title=Masturbation and Clitoridectomy: A Nineteenth-Century View|journal=JAMA|volume=186|issue=3|pages=246–248|url=http://jama.ama-assn.org/cgi/content/summary/186/3/246|pmid=14057114}}&lt;/ref&gt; This procedure is also ritual in certain tribes such as the [[Maasai people|Maasai]] in Kenya and Tanzania.

